484
00:31:05,284 --> 00:31:08,291
with all the systems 
we have discussed today

485
00:31:08,291 --> 00:31:13,204
and of course much more ancillaries
to make the system work overall.

486
00:31:13,204 --> 00:31:15,758
You'll also notice the size of the plant

487
00:31:15,758 --> 00:31:21,119
as compared to the typical size
of a human person here.

488
00:31:21,119 --> 00:31:28,767
ITER will be aiming at providing
a fusion gain, capital Q of 10 or more,

489
00:31:28,767 --> 00:31:31,906
a fusion power of about half a gigawatt

490
00:31:31,906 --> 00:31:34,744
for a duration of several hundreds 
of seconds.

491
00:31:34,744 --> 00:31:36,995
It will therefore be 
the first demonstration

492
00:31:36,995 --> 00:31:40,240
of the scientific 
and technological feasibility of fusion

493
00:31:40,240 --> 00:31:42,351
and of its safety.

494
00:31:42,351 --> 00:31:45,414
We can now summarize the lecture.

495
00:31:45,414 --> 00:31:49,867
We have seen today that we have two 
approaches on earth to reach the conditions

496
00:31:49,867 --> 00:31:51,946
that are necessary 
for a fusion reactor to work:

497
00:31:52,099 --> 00:31:54,216
inertial and magnetic.

498
00:31:54,216 --> 00:31:58,228
For inertial confinement, we have seen
that the efficiency of the driver

499
00:31:58,228 --> 00:32:02,335
and of its conversion to pellet energy,
and heating are crucial.

500
00:32:02,335 --> 00:32:07,252
The implosion of the pellet 
can be helped by the rocket effect.

501
00:32:08,653 --> 00:32:12,118
We have seen that 
the indirect drive can help,

502
00:32:12,170 --> 00:32:15,023
improving the symmetry of the implosion.

503
00:32:15,023 --> 00:32:17,055
We have also noticed 
that there are challenges

504
00:32:17,055 --> 00:32:19,519
on the physics side and on
the engineering side.

505
00:32:19,519 --> 00:32:20,959
On the physics side,

506
00:32:20,959 --> 00:32:22,798
the heating of the core
and the stability of the pellet

507
00:32:22,798 --> 00:32:24,569
are the most important ones.

508
00:32:24,569 --> 00:32:26,275
On the engineering side,

509
00:32:26,275 --> 00:32:29,419
we need to really address the issue
of the cost of the pellet

510
00:32:29,419 --> 00:32:32,734
and of the repetition rate
of the pulses.

511
00:32:32,734 --> 00:32:36,663
We have introduced the concept 
of magnetic confinement

512
00:32:36,663 --> 00:32:39,219
based on magnetic fields
to hold the plasma together

513
00:32:39,219 --> 00:32:41,671
in a cleverly designed cage.

514
00:32:41,671 --> 00:32:44,323
We have seen that toroidal devices
are needed

515
00:32:44,323 --> 00:32:46,666
for this cage to be efficient,

516
00:32:46,666 --> 00:32:50,975
and we have mentioned 
and briefly introduced the ITER project

517
00:32:50,975 --> 00:32:54,839
which will be the one to provide us
with burning plasmas,

518
00:32:54,839 --> 00:32:56,443
and therefore the one 
that will demonstrate

519
00:32:56,443 --> 00:33:00,054
that fusion is feasible
both scientifically and technologically,

520
00:33:00,054 --> 00:33:01,594
and that it is safe.

521
00:33:01,594 --> 00:33:04,238
In terms of magnetic confinement,

522
00:33:04,238 --> 00:33:09,099
we did not go into much depth
